\f2\b\fs32 Compression fittings
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::3>
\f1\fs32  are made up of three basic elements: the 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::3>
\f2\b\fs32 compression nut
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::3>
\f1\fs32  , the 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::3>
\f2\b\fs32 ferrule
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::3>
\f1\fs32  , and the body.  The tubing is slipped through the nut and the ferrule and then inserted into the end of the body.  By tightening the nut/screw the ferrule is forced into the fitting body. As the ferrule  moves axially into the fitting body, the body\'92s angled shape compresses the end of the ferrule onto the outer diameter of the tubing. It is this radial compression that creates a leak tight seal between the fitting, ferrule, and tubing, and gives the compression fitting its name.\
\pard\sb40\sa40\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

